sense.s:
hadajato, (S,) inf. n. hadajN, (L,) She (a camel) yearned towards her young one; 
								HanRato EalaI waladihaA; (S, L;) as also 
							thdRjt↓; (L;) [and, app., uttered the cry produced by yearning towards her young one: see below:] or the latter signifies she was affectionate to her young one. (S, K.)

hadajapN, (a subst., L,) The yearning, or the cry produced by yearning towards her young one, of a camel; 
								Haniynu AlnRaAqapi: (K:) or the yearning of a she-camel towards her young one; 
								Haniynu AlnRaAqupi 
								EalaI waladihaA. (S, L.)

Also, (assumed tropical:) 
								A wind that has a sound; 
								lahaA HaniynN: (S, L:) from HanRati AlnRaAqapu. (L.)

hrt EiroDahu (S) aor. and

							haruta

								, inf. n. harotN, (K,) He wounded his reputation; syn. TaEana fiyhi; (S:) as also harad and haraTa, (TA.) [Accord. to the K, harata seems to signify the same as TaEana absolutely: but in the TA the signification is restricted as above;

UinRamaA sumRiyta haAniYFA 
								litahoniYa, or litahonaOa; the former is the reading of El-Umawee; the latter, of Ks; Thou art only named Háni (Giver, or Nourisher,) that thou mayest give, accord. to both readings; or that thou mayest nourish, or maintain, and supply people's wants; 
								ltEwl wtkfI: (TA:) [such is said to be the meaning of lthnO here:] and accord. to El-Umawee, lthnY signifies litumoriYa, (S,) [which is app. the same as ltEwl]. A proverb: said to him who is known for his beneficence, in order that he may continue to do as he has been wont. (TA.)
